{"cursor":"20409","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n, ca. 1100]]\n.  Saint Agnes appears to her friends in a vision.]] in painted Limoges enamel\n   on a copper plaque, by Jacques I Laudin]]\n\n'Vitreous enamel', also 'porcelain enamel' in US English, is a material made by\nfusing powdered glass to a substrate by firing, usually between . The powder\nmelts, flows, and then hardens to a smooth, durable coating on metal, or on\nglass or ceramics. The term \"enamel\" is most often restricted to work on metal,\nwhich is the subject of this article. Enamelled glass is also called \"painted\".\nFired enamelware is an integrated layered composite of glass and metal. The word\nenamel comes from the Old High German word smelzan (to smelt) via the Old French\nesmail. Campbell, 6 Used as a noun, \"an enamel\" is a usually small\ndecorative object, coated with enamel coating. Enameling is an old and widely-\nadopted technology, for most of its history mainly used in jewelry and\ndecorative art. Since the 19th century the term applies also to industrial\nmaterials and many metal consumer objects, such as some cooking vessels,\ndishwashers, laundry machines, sinks and tubs, etc. \"Enamelled\" and \"enamelling\"\nare the preferred spellings in British English, while \"enameled\" and \"enameling\"\nare preferred in American English.\n","linknr":571,"url":"Vitreous_enamel","recorded":1362481749,"links":67,"instances":["country","casket"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Pottery","Decorative arts","Coatings","Art materials","Jewellery making","Glass applications","Glass compositions","Glass art","Ceramic art","Vitreous enamel|","Ceramic glazes"],"headings":["History","Properties","Techniques of artistic enameling","Industrial Enamel Application","Gallery","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Medallio